"prompt":[
" ",
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"a12f3c",
"children":[
"In addition to supportive care, which of the following is the most appropriate treatment?"
]
},
" "
],
"options":[
{
"letter":"A",
"text":{
"__html":"Artesunate"
}
},
{
"letter":"B",
"text":{
"__html":"Atovaquone-proguanil"
}
},
{
"letter":"C",
"text":{
"__html":"Primaquine"
}
},
{
"letter":"D",
"text":{
"__html":"Tafenoquine"
}
}
],
"keypoints":[
{
"type":"keypoint",
"hlId":"dc5f28",
"children":[
"Patients with severe malaria should be treated initially with intravenous artesunate and then transitioned to an oral antimalarial regimen when clinically stable."
]
}
],
"exposition":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"f20c3b",
"children":[
"Intravenous artesunate is the most appropriate treatment for this patient (",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Option A"
]
},
"). He has severe ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Plasmodium falciparum"
]
},
" malaria that is likely mefloquine resistant, which is becoming increasingly prevalent in various parts of Southeast Asia, including Laos and Cambodia. On the peripheral blood smear, thin, often multiple rings on the inner surface of young and old erythrocytes, as well as banana-shaped gametocytes, are distinctive morphologic characteristics of ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"P. falciparum"
]
},
" species. Severe malaria primarily occurs with ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"P. falciparum"
]
},
" and is defined by a high degree of parasitemia (>10%) accompanied by one or more clinical (e.g., pulmonary edema, seizures and confusion, bleeding, jaundice, shock) and laboratory (e.g., severe anemia, kidney injury, metabolic acidosis, hypoglycemia, hemoglobinuria) criteria. The spleen functions to filter and clear malaria-infected erythrocytes, so patients who have undergone splenectomy have an increased risk of developing more severe disease and dying from this protozoan infection. Artesunate is the drug of choice, with transition to an oral antimalarial medication such as artemether-lumefantrine, atovaquone-proguanil, doxycycline, or quinine sulfate to complete the course of treatment when significant improvement has been achieved. Intensive medical care, including hemodynamic and respiratory support, management of fluid and electrolytes, blood replacement, and possibly hemodialysis, is also immediately required."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"e35051",
"children":[
"Atovaquone-proguanil (",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Option B"
]
},
") and quinine sulfate can be used to treat all malarial species regardless of chloroquine sensitivity, but they are not recommended for severe malaria."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"fe75f0",
"children":[
"All ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Plasmodium"
]
},
" species invade hepatocytes. However, only ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"P. vivax"
]
},
" and ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"P. ovale"
]
},
" have a latent hepatic stage (hypnozoites). Following the treatment of the erythrocytic stage, primaquine or tafenoquine (",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Option C, D"
]
},
") is given to prevent clinical relapse by eradicating persistent infection in the liver. These drugs are not used in the treatment of erythrocytic malaria or for severe malaria."
]
}
],
